arch:property.oc:show_val: A small size unit (relatively little larger than a standard small size unit). There are well preserved pieces in dry sieve sample. And the surface conditions are quite similar at especially big pieces, and generally pretty good although not completely fresh. Almost whole mandible of sheep/goat (with incisors, showing minimal postdepositional disturbance), a humerus, quite a lot of long bone shaft fragments, rib fragments, some O3 size carpals and some whole teeth are present in dry sieve sample. The pieces in the flotation sample are more fragmented. They look rolled, trampled and kicked around. There are still some carpals and long bone fragments. Also in both dry sieve and flotation sample there are couple of O7 pieces present. %10 burning. The survival of a complete infantile radius with a bit of its unfused epiphysis still in place shows that at least some areas were quite undisturbed. On the other hand, there is little coherence. There are bits of many different animals (mostly sheep/goat), with little that goes together. So it looks like a slow accumulation of waste from daily household consumption, with little subsequent disturbance. Probably a dirty room fill, or a bit of a midden.

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
